sentence: Fritz Kreisler (February 2, 1875 – January 29, 1962) was an Austrian-born American violinist and composer.
Kreisler was born in Vienna, the son of Anna (née Reches) and Samuel Kreisler, a doctor.
He then returned to Austria and applied for a position in the Vienna Philharmonic, but was turned down by the concertmaster Arnold Rosé.

He also wrote operettas, including Apple Blossoms in 1919 and Sissy in 1932, a string quartet, and cadenzas, including ones for Brahms's Violin Concerto, Paganini's D major Violin Concerto, and Beethoven's Violin Concerto.
His cadenzas for the Beethoven concerto are the ones most often played by violinists today.
He wrote the music for the 1936 movie The King Steps Out directed by Josef von Sternberg, based on the early years of Empress Elisabeth of Austria.

Fritz Kreisler (February 2, 1875 – January 29, 1962) was an Austrian-born American violinist and composer.
Although it derived in many respects from the Franco-Belgian school, his style is nonetheless reminiscent of the gemütlich (cozy) lifestyle of pre-war Vienna.
Kreisler was born in Vienna, the son of Anna (née Reches) and Samuel Kreisler, a doctor.
He studied at the Vienna Conservatory under Anton Bruckner, Jakob Dont and Joseph Hellmesberger Jr., and in Paris, where his teachers included Léo Delibes, Lambert Massart and Jules Massenet.
While in Paris, he won the "Premier Grand Prix de Rome" gold medal at the age of 12, competing against 40 other players, all of whom were at least 20 years of age.
He made his United States debut at the Steinway Hall in New York City on November 10, 1888, and his first tour of the United States in 1888–1889 with Moriz Rosenthal.
He made his United States debut at the Steinway Hall in New York City on November 10, 1888, and his first tour of the United States in 1888–1889 with Moriz Rosenthal.
He made his United States debut at the Steinway Hall in New York City on November 10, 1888, and his first tour of the United States in 1888–1889 with Moriz Rosenthal.
He then returned to Austria and applied for a position in the Vienna Philharmonic, but was turned down by the concertmaster Arnold Rosé.
It was this concert and a series of American tours from 1901 to 1903 that brought him real acclaim.
He arrived in New York on November 24, 1914, and spent the remainder of the war in America.
He returned to Europe in 1924, living first in Berlin, then moving to France in 1938.
He returned to Europe in 1924, living first in Berlin, then moving to France in 1938.
He returned to Europe in 1924, living first in Berlin, then moving to France in 1938.
Shortly thereafter, at the outbreak of World War II, he settled once again in the United States, becoming a naturalized citizen in 1943.
Struck by a truck while crossing a street in New York, he suffered a fractured skull and was in a coma for over a week.
Kreisler died of a heart condition aggravated by old age in New York City in 1962.
